== How to Play Go with Concord Go Rules? ==

* __When passing, place a pass stone in your opponent's prisoner bowl.__ This gives the opponent one point, but since games typically end with two passes, this does not change the result.
* __The first and last pass must be made by different players.__
* __Count every surrounded point as territory, even in seki.__ Seki (mutual life positions) eyes are points.
* __When scoring is unclear, continue playing until all dead stones are captured.__ This does not change the game's final score.

== Why Concord Go Rules? ==

Concord Go Rules combine the best features of Japanese/Korean, Chinese, AGA and Taiwan rules.

{{special:table | border=1 | cellpadding=5
|= Feature |= Japanese%%%& Korean |= Chinese |= AGA |= Taiwan |= __Concord__
|-
| Territory Counting | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ | ❌ | ✅
|-
| Area Counting | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅
|-
| Every Point Matters | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ | ✅
|-
| Resolution by Play | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅
|-
| Game Ends with Two Passes | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ | ✅
}}

Concord Go Rules achieve these important goals:

* __Both territory and area counting work.__ Both methods always give the same score.
* __Every point matters.__ Small endgame mistakes can alter the final score by a single point.
* __Resolution by Play.__ Games can continue until all dead stones are captured.

